indicator.description:
-Continued support for reform by the executive and legislative branches; 
-Increase in numbers of civic groups and communities directly able to provide inputs on reform; 
-Number of civic and community-level dialogues around reform with the participation of national and local government officials; 
-Completion of HR-related, rule of law, justice, and security sector assessments and Action Plan and the integration of these results into governance reform;
- Roadmaps for key reform processes available; 
- Number of new long-term programmes partially or totally funded;
- Number of policy inputs made by UNDP integrated into government plans;
- Number of SSE/TC  initiatives facilitated that lead to long-term cooperation;
-Completion of risk and vulnerability assessments, with specific gender and human rights components; 
successful development and adoption of mitigation measures; 
-Level of community participation in local-level dialogue and confidence-building forums; 
-Development of policy framework on transitional justice and accountability; number of quick wins in areas restored to government control; 
-Development and adoption of comprehensive recovery policy.

baseline.comment:
-Only a few reform areas are sketched out with a road map but quality remains average and content lacks inclusive consultation;
-UNDP has developed a series of short concept notes as immediate response to transition & conflict in April 2014 but long-term umbrella programmes missing;  
-UNDP has a mixed track-record on influencing policy processes in spite of convincing results on the ground;
-No South-South exchanges facilitated since Maidan happened;
-Initial assessments have been conducted of IDP and recovery needs, but have focused primarily on basic needs and infrastructure; assessments have not yet covered reconciliation, human rights, and gender;
-National recovery coordination mechanism has been established, but comprehensive recovery policy not yet established;
-Risks of inter-community tensions in the four oblasts bordering Luhansk, Donesk, and Crimea have not yet been assessed, and systematic local capacities for dialogue and confidence-building not yet established;
-Quick win initiatives have only been launched in Slaviansk, but not comprehensively, and not in all areas restored to government control;
-Issues of transitional justice, human rights, and rule of law in the conflict-affected areas have not yet been subjected to a national debate, and a comprehensive national policy not yet developed.

target.comment:
-At least two key reform areas are framed by a detailed strategy and road map that has reflect contributions from concerned stakeholders;
- At least three new long-term programmes partially or totally funded, including: a comprehensive programme on integrated recovery for the Donets Basin, a decentralisation programme and one in a new area (e.g. community security & social cohesion, political party culture & civic engagement, anti-corruption);
-UNDP specific substantive inputs incorporated in at least two reform areas; 
-Two long-term SSE/TCs supported;
-At least five quick win initiatives launched with UNDP support in Luhansk and Donetsk;
-National recovery and support policy for IDPs and conflict-affected areas developed;
-Comprehensive vulnerability, risks, and needs assessments conducted for Luhansk and Donetsk and four neighboring oblasts, integrating gender, human rights, and reconciliation dimensions;
-National policy on transitional justice developed;
-Local confidence-building forums established in all districts of the four oblasts bordering Luhansk and Donetsk.

actual.comment:
-The capacity of the country office in programming and resource mobilization strengthened, through the recruitment of two international advisors; one specializing in democratic governance and the other on recovery and stabilization. 
-Various consultancies were fielded that supported the Secretariat of Constitutional Reform; 
-Parliamentary Reform and Rule of Law and Stabilization programmes fieled and developed;
-In partnership with the Office of the Ombudsman in Ukraine, the GRRIP supported the implementation of the survey on decentralization and rights of women in rural areas;
-UNDP has been instrumental in leading the provision of technical assistance to the inter-ministerial, joint working group on the Recovery and Peacebuiding Assesment (RPA), whereby a governance architecture for ensuring policy coherence and coordination on the RPA was agreed;
- Dialogue Platform launched.

baseline.comment:
1. 0 economic infrastructure facilities recovered 
2. 0 people employed at cash for work, public works and temporary jobs programmes;
3. 0 persons provided with new professions/ skills through trainings; 
4. 0 representatives of local administrations, PES trained on creating enabling environment for economic, business and employment development on local level
5. 0 business support institutions supported;
6. 0 new small and medium-sized businesses/enterprises started activities

target.comment:
1. At least 10 economic infrastructure facilities recovered 
2. At least 1,000 people employed at cash for work, public works and temporary jobs programmes;
3. At least 300 persons provided with new professions/ skills through trainings; 
4. At least 50 representatives of local administrations, PES trained on creating enabling environment for economic, business and employment development on local level
5. At least 5 business support institutions supported;
6. At least 100 new small and medium-sized businesses/enterprises started activities

indicator.description:
Change in baseline quantitative international indices relating to corruption (WGI, CPI) and improvements as suggested by regular national research (national report on corruption in line with UN standards, as envisaged by Anticorruption Strategy 2014-2017);
Performance of the national corruption prevention architecture assessed as satisfactory by international review mechanisms of CoE (GRECO) and OECD (ACPN  Istanbul Anti-Corruption Action Plan);
Existence of an efficient, accessible and transparent national system of assets declarations submission and verification.

baseline.comment:
Ukraines current position in indices / public polls regarding corruption is: CPI = 144/177 for 2013 (20th percentile); WGI control of corruption index = -1,09; Razumkov Center 2013 corruption data = 82% citizens believe corruption is pervasive or very widespread in public sector;
No assessments of the updated corruption prevention architecture have yet been produced. First of such assessments that could be used as baseline are to appear in spring 2015 through the OECD (ACPN  Istanbul Anti-Corruption Action Plan);
Absence of national system for digital submission and verification of assets declarations is in place.

indicator.description:
Assessment of progress on human rights as elicited from the third UPR review cycle in 2017;
OO regional coverage;
Existence and operationalization of a National Human Rights Strategy and presumably rolled out through a subsequent Action Plan which is developed with application of SMART-goal principles and foresees thorough monitoring by the OO and the civil society;

baseline.comment:
Baseline to be taken from UPR recommendations of the second round of 2012; 
3 existing regional offices in Dnipropetrovsk, Lviv and Zhytomyr with 5 full-time civil servants. On top of this, in 9 oblasts a piloting system of OO regional coordinators for public relations was activated through the DHRP Programme supported by DMFA; No baseline for rights-holder satisfaction;
Currently no National Human Rights Strategy / Action Plan is in place to take international recommendations and obligations forwards in a systematic manner.
